</style></head><body><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Santiago’s Github Page:</p><p class="s1" style="padding-top: 1pt;padding-left: 25pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">Analysis for Century 21 Ames</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 25pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">Vo Nguyen | Santiago Gutierrez</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><a href="https://vochannguyen.github.io/" style=" color: black; font-family:Calibri, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none; font-size: 12pt;" target="_blank">Vo Nguyen’s Github Page: </a><a href="https://vochannguyen.github.io/" target="_blank">https://vochannguyen.github.io/</a></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Introduction</h1><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 9pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">As requested by Century 21 Ames, we have analyzed nearly 3,000 homes with about 80 categorical variables that describe residential homes in Ames, Iowa in order to build and test predictive models that allows us to estimate home prices.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">In this report, we begin by studying and discussing the effects that Gross Living Area has on Sales Price for three specific Neighborhoods in Ames. We do so by finding linear relationships between variables, building a model, and then tuning our model to be more accurate.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Additionally, using a multitude of variables, we build predictive models for sales price and then analyze the accuracy of each to determine the best fitting model. We use four different variable selection methods to decide which variables were of importance and used those to build the four models.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Data Description</h1><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 9pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">The data used in this analysis has been provided by Dean De Cock through Kaggle. The data describes the sale of individual homes in Ames, Iowa between 2006 and 2010. The data is divided between two sets – a training set for building our models and a test set used to test the models. Our predictive models are built using 1,460 observations and specific variables (of the 79 provided) from the training data set. We test our models using additional information from 1,458 homes in the Ames area to predict the sales prices and examine the accuracy.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Question 1 Analysis</h1><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-top: 9pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">The Problem</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Century 21 Ames only sells houses in the NAmes, Edwards, and BrkSide neighborhoods and would like to determine how the sales price of homes is related to square footage per 100 sq ft. of living area (GrLivArea) and if the relationship depends on which neighborhood the house is located in.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Build and Fit the Model</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Assuming independent observations, we begin by investigating to see if there exists a linear relationship between our primary explanatory variable, GrLivArea, and Sales Price. By creating a simple scatter plot, we are able to see what appears to be a pretty positive, linear relationship - see Plot 1.1 [Appendix]. There is also some evidence of outliers, which is supported by plotting the probability distributions and boxplot of GrLivArea, as seen in Plot 1.2. We also added an interaction between GrLivArea and Neighborhood because we found slight evidence of the Neighborhood having a possible effect on GrLivArea (Plot 1.1), which makes sense logically - a wealthier neighborhood will probably have larger homes, and thus, a higher SalePrice. Given the basic assumptions being met, we can run our model below, analyze, and adjust to meet the necessary assumptions.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 25pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">The Model:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s2" style="padding-left: 25pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">μ(SalePrice) = b0 + b1(GrLivArea) + b2*BrkSide + B3*Edwards + b4(GrLivArea*BrkSide) + b5(GrLivArea*Edwards)</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Checking Assumptions</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Our initial model depicted by Plot 1.3 [Appendix] confirms the existence of outliers. With the model as-is, we have obtained an adjusted R-Square of 0.44. Overall, the model looks decent but will likely improve with the removal of said outliers. Based on the plots, there does not appear to be any major trends or any evidence against a normal distribution with constant variance. We already assume that the observations are independent.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Comparing Competing Models</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">By creating table 1.4 [Appendix], we are able to easily identify the outliers based on residual and</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Cook’s D. We chose a Cook’s D threshold of 0.02.</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 7pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">and found eleven outliers, see Table 1.4 [Appendix]. Given that the majority of Cook’s D were below</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">0.01 with a few just above the threshold, so we decided to increase the threshold to 0.02. Now, the</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">model appears to be much better fit - see Plots 1.5 - 1.8. We ran the model without those outliers and obtained an R-Squared of 0.5244, which can be seen in Table 1.5.</p><h2 style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Parameters</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Our resulting parameter estimates from our model can be seen in Table 1.6 [Appendix].</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 25pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">Fitted Models:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s3" style="padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 229%;text-align: justify;">μ(SalePrice|NAmes) = 80157.51 + 49.66(GrLivArea) μ(SalePrice|BrkSide) = 22396.27 + 84.17(GrLivArea) μ(SalePrice|Edwards) = 63756.64 + 46.25(GrLivArea)</p><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Given our results, we can estimate that:</p><ul id="l1"><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">For a home in NAmes, holding BrkSide &amp; Edwards constant, a 100 sqft. increase in gross living area is associated with a mean increase of $4,966 in sale price. We are 95% confident that the increase in sale price is between $4,197 and $5,734.</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">For a home in BrkSide, holding NAmes &amp; Edwards constant, a 100 sqft. increase in gross living area is associated with a mean increase of $8,417 in sale price. We are 95% confident that the increase in sale price is between $6,861 and $9,972.</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">For a home in Edwards, holding NAmes &amp; BrkSide constant, a 100 sqft. increase in gross living area is associated with a mean increase of $4,625 in sale price. We are 95% confident that the increase in sale price is between $3,121 and $6,129.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Conclusion</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">The model is quite good given our p-value &lt; 0.0001 for the F-test. Our adjusted R² tells us that 52.44% of the variability of Sale Price can be explained by Gross Living Area. Given the $ increase per 100 sqft., one can infer that a home in BrkSide will likely cost/increase more than a home in NAmes or Edwards; however, the mean home sale price appears to be greatest in Edwards - Table 1.3 [Appendix]. Given that this is an observational study, causal inference cannot be attributed to any parameter with relation to sale price.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">R Shiny App: Sale Price vs. Gross Living Area</h2><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><a href="https://santigtz95.shinyapps.io/STAT_RShiny/">https://santigtz95.shinyapps.io/STAT_RShiny/</a></p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><a href="https://vochannguyen.shinyapps.io/Stats1Shiny/">https://vochannguyen.shinyapps.io/Stats1Shiny/</a></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Question 2 Analysis</h1><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">The Problem</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Build the most predictive model for sales prices of homes in all of Ames, Iowa - including all neighborhoods. Produce four models using: forward selection, backward selection, stepwise selection, and a custom-built model. Generate an adjusted R², CV Press, and Kaggle Score for each of the models. Clearly describe which model is the best fit in terms of being able to predict future sale prices of homes in Ames.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Build and Fit the Models</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Before building the model, we remove the outliers we found in question 1. We also inspected the data to identify and remove variables with large amounts of NA/missing values, as well as those with unnecessary application. Once we had our “good” variables, we built our initial model.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="614" height="154" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr><tr><td><img width="614" height="77" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr><tr><td><img width="614" height="77" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr></table></span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: justify;">We begin every model by checking for linearity, primarily between numerical variables. From there, we select those that appear to have some linear relation. Some relations appear to be better with sale price logged, so we perform the transformation and select the linear relation variables. We remove outliers using Cook’s D / residual data and proceed with our analysis of the models.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Forward Model</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Build and Run Forward Selection Model. Using cross validation, we found 19x potential variables with very good results in terms of our R², AIC, SBC, CV Press, and RMSE. See table 2.1 [Appendix].</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: left;">R² = 91.91%</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: left;">CV Press = 20.7020</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Backward Model</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Build and Run Backward Selection Model. Using cross validation, the model eliminated 5x variables and produced good results in terms of our R², AIC, SBC, CV Press, and RMSE. However, the slightly better results (in comparison to forward selection model) required a lot more parameters. See table 2.2 [Appendix].</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: left;">R² = 92.32%</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: left;">CV Press = 19.8670</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Stepwise Model</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Build and Run Stepwise Selection Model. Using cross validation, we found 14x potential variables with very good results in terms of our R², AIC, SBC, CV Press, and RMSE. See table 2.3 [Appendix].</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 15pt;text-align: left;">R² = 91.62%</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: left;">CV Press = 20.7020</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Custom-Backward Model</h2><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 114%;text-align: left;">Given the results from the backward selection model, we build and run a custom-backward selection model with 5x variables eliminated. Using the custom-backward model, we have maintained a good R² and slightly reduced the CV Press, as well as a very good Kaggle score. See table 2.4 [Appendix].</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 15pt;text-align: left;">R² = 92.32%</p></li><li data-list-text="●"><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 113pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: left;">CV Press = 19.3796</p></li></ul><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left:
